; Regression test: Python plugin CostSpec serialization
;
; Bug: When Python plugins processed transactions with cost specs, the
; cost amount would be lost during roundtrip serialization because the
; Python compat layer was reading the wrong field name.
;
; Root cause: The compat layer used _parse_cost() which expects a "number"
; field, but Rust sends CostSpec format with "number_per"/"number_total".
; This caused cost specs to have None for the amount after roundtrip.
;
; This file demonstrates a scenario where a Python plugin modifies
; transactions and the cost information must be preserved.

option "operating_currency" "USD"

2020-01-01 open Assets:Stock  AAPL  "FIFO"
2020-01-01 open Assets:Cash
2020-01-01 open Income:Dividends
2020-01-01 open Income:CapitalGains

; Use a Python plugin that processes transactions
; (e.g., auto_accounts, zerosum, or any custom plugin)
plugin "beancount.plugins.auto_accounts"

; Buy stock with explicit cost
2024-01-15 * "Buy AAPL"
  Assets:Stock   10 AAPL {150.00 USD, 2024-01-15}
  Assets:Cash   -1500 USD

; Sell with empty cost spec - FIFO should match the lot above
; After Python plugin processes this, the cost spec should still be intact
2024-06-15 * "Sell AAPL"
  Assets:Stock   -5 AAPL {}
  Assets:Cash    875 USD  ; $175/share
  Income:CapitalGains

; If cost was lost during Python plugin roundtrip, this would fail
; because the lot matching wouldn't find {150.00 USD, 2024-01-15}
2024-06-16 balance Assets:Stock  5 AAPL
